Time Complexity :-
addNum()
    Heap insertion/removal:
    O(log n)

findMedian()
    Just peek top:
    O(1)

Important Intuition

Think of it like:

    LEFT HALF  | RIGHT HALF
    (max heap) | (min heap)

    We only care about the border elements:

    max(left)
    min(right)

Those are enough to calculate median.

Why Insert into small First?

    This trick automatically maintains ordering.

Flow:

    small -> large -> rebalance

    This guarantees : all elements in small <= all in large without complicated checks.

Heap Diagram
    Numbers: 1 2 3 4 5 6

    small(maxHeap)      large(minHeap)

          3                   4
        /   \               /   \
       2     1             5     6

    Median:

    (3 + 4)/2

    = 3.5


class MedianFinder {

    PriorityQueue<Integer> small; // max heap
    PriorityQueue<Integer> large; // min heap

    public MedianFinder() {

        // Max Heap
        small = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> b - a);

        // Min Heap
        large = new PriorityQueue<>();
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {

        // Step 1: add into max heap
            small.offer(num);

        // Step 2: move largest from small to large
        large.offer(small.poll());

        // Step 3: balance sizes
        if (large.size() > small.size()) {
            small.offer(large.poll());
        }
    }

    public double findMedian() {

        // odd count
        if (small.size() > large.size()) {
            return small.peek();
        }

        // even count
        return (small.peek() + large.peek()) / 2.0;
    }
}


This problem is about finding the most repeated numbers in an array.

Concept

First, count how many times each number appears.

Example:

nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]

Frequencies become:

1 -> 3
2 -> 2
3 -> 1

Now we just need the top k numbers with highest frequency.

Best common approach: HashMap + Min Heap
Step 1: Count frequency

Use a HashMap<Integer, Integer>.

Step 2: Keep only top k elements

Use a min heap of size k.

Why min heap?

Because we want to remove the element with the smallest frequency whenever heap size goes beyond k.

So:

heap stores pairs like (number, frequency)
smallest frequency stays on top
if heap size > k, remove top

At the end, the heap contains the k most frequent elements.

Why this works

Suppose we have these frequencies:

1 -> 5
2 -> 3
3 -> 2
4 -> 1

If k = 2, we only want [1, 2].

Using a min heap of size 2:

insert 1(5)
insert 2(3)
insert 3(2) → heap size becomes 3, remove smallest frequency → remove 3(2)
insert 4(1) → remove 4(1)

Final heap has 1(5) and 2(3).

Java Solution
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {
        // 1. Count frequency
        Map<Integer, Integer> freqMap = new HashMap<>();
        for (int num : nums) {
            freqMap.put(num, freqMap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        // 2. Min heap based on frequency
        PriorityQueue<int[]> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(
            (a, b) -> a[1] - b[1]
        );

        // 3. Add all elements into heap
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : freqMap.entrySet()) {
            minHeap.offer(new int[]{entry.getKey(), entry.getValue()});

            // keep only k elements
            if (minHeap.size() > k) {
                minHeap.poll();
            }
        }

        // 4. Extract result
        int[] result = new int[k];
        int index = 0;
        while (!minHeap.isEmpty()) {
            result[index++] = minHeap.poll()[0];
        }

        return result;
    }
}
Dry Run

For:

nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3], k = 2

Frequency map:

1 -> 3
2 -> 2
3 -> 1

Heap operations:

insert (1,3)
insert (2,2)
insert (3,1) → size becomes 3, remove (3,1)

Final heap:

(2,2), (1,3)

Answer:

[2,1]

Any order is allowed, so this is correct.

Time Complexity
Counting frequency: O(n)
Heap operations: O(n log k)

So total:

O(n log k)
Space Complexity
HashMap: O(n)
Heap: O(k)
One-line intuition

Count first, then keep only the k strongest frequencies using a min heap.